				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$C{a}^{2+}+2HC{O}_{3}^{-}\leftrightarrow CaC{O}_{3}+C{O}_{2}+{H}_{2}O$$\end{document}Ca2++2HCO3−↔CaCO3+CO2+H2OIt is clear that a change in related ions concentration, moisture and/or temperature will alter the carbonate dissolution/precipitation equilibrium, which would lead to a change in soil CO2 concentration. Apparently, adding Ca2+ in soil profile would be beneficial for carbonate precipitation and also CO2 creation15,31, which could partly explain why soil CO2 was the highest under Ca treatment in winter.
